@@rYou have descended to the lowest circle of Hell. A vast frozen lake called
@@rCocytus stretches before you, its surface broken by the heads and torsos of
@@rthe treacherous, frozen in the ice at various depths. The closer to the
@@rcenter, the deeper the sinners are submerged. A terrible cold wind blows
@@racross the ice, the source of which becomes terrifyingly apparent. The
@@rcold here is not natural cold -- it is the cold of absolute betrayal, the
@@rfreezing of trust itself made physical. The faces visible above the ice
@@rwear expressions of permanent, horrified recognition, as if they have
@@rfinally understood something too late. The ice is perfectly clear in some
@@rsections, allowing you to see down through layers of frozen traitors to
@@rdepths that suggest the lake is far deeper than it has any right to be.
@@rYour breath does not fog here -- the cold takes it away before it can.
