The Bridge of Sighs~
@@rAn ancient stone bridge arches over a river of liquid shadow that flows
@@rwithout sound and without source. The bridge is wide and well-maintained,
@@rwhich stands out here as either an architectural mercy or a deliberate
@@rcruelty -- leading souls somewhere worse on a comfortable road. Shades
@@rwalk across it in both directions with the focused purpose of those who
@@rhave somewhere to be and prefer not to think about where. The handrails
@@rare carved with the faces of famous betrayers in detailed cameos. The
@@rliquid below is not water and not fire but moves with the intent of both.
@@rSometimes shapes rise in it briefly, face-upward and still, before being
@@rreclaimed. The sighing the bridge is named for is constant and comes
@@rfrom the stone itself, as if the bridge shares the general ambience.
