#1633
The Obsidian Gallery~
@@rA long gallery of polished obsidian walls displays the history of Hell's
@@rconquest of the damned in scenes carved with brutal artistry. The earliest
@@rscenes show the Fall itself -- angels becoming demons in cascades of
@@rlight and fire. Later scenes show the construction of Hell's architecture,
@@rwith damned souls used as building material in ways that explain some
@@rof the more unusual load-bearing structures. Recent scenes -- rendered
@@rin a style suggesting the carver was working with enthusiasm -- depict
@@rfamous arrivals and the entertainments arranged for them. The gallery
@@ris lit by floating spheres of captive fire that follow viewers as they
@@rwalk, ensuring nothing is missed. A daemon curator lurks at the far end,
@@ravailable to answer questions in a voice like a file on glass.
