#1679
The Vault of the Misers~
@@rIn a cut-back alcove off the plain of weights, the worst of the hoarders
@@rare confined behind iron bars of their own imagining -- their greed so
@@rabsolute in life that Hell shaped their prison from its memory. Stacks of
@@rcounterfeit infernal coin fill the vault floor, worth nothing and untouchable
@@rthrough the bars regardless. The misers press their faces to the bars and
@@rcount the coins in obsessive murmur, always arriving at the same sum, always
@@rstarting again. A single greed archon keeps watch, dressed in the finery of
@@rthose it once served, its ledger recording debts that can never be collected
@@rfrom souls that own nothing and never will. The lock on the vault has no
@@rkeyhole. There is no door. The bars are a courtesy of Hell's dark architects,
@@rwho understood that a cage is most effective when the prisoner believes in it.
